description: From Middle English whelp, from Old English hwelp, from Proto-West Germanic *hwelp, from Proto-Germanic *hwelpaz (compare Dutch welp, German Welpe, Old Norse hvelpr, Norwegian Nynorsk kvelp, Danish hvalp), from pre-Germanic *k ∑elbos, of uncertain origin.

entries.meaning: A young offspring of a canid (ursid, felid, pinniped), especially of a dog or a wolf, the young of a bear or similar mammal (lion, tiger, seal); a pup, wolf cub.
(derogatory) An insolent youth; a mere child.
examples: That awkward whelp with his money bags would have made his entrance.

entries.meaning: One of several wooden strips to prevent wear on a windlass on a clipper-era ship.
A tooth on a sprocket wheel (compare sprocket and cog).

description: From Middle English whelpen, from Old English hwelpian, derived from hwelp.

verbs.description: whelp (third-person singular simple present whelps, present participle whelping, simple past and past participle whelped)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive, of she-dog, she-wolf, vixen, etc.) To give birth.
examples: The she-wolf whelped a large litter of cubs.
